s part of the support that JavaScript provides to enable the natural use of the Windows Runtime.","pos":[6326,6443]},{"content":"Namespaces and class names are Pascal-cased.","pos":[6444,6488]},{"content":"Member names are camel-cased except for event names, which are all lowercase.","pos":[6489,6566]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Using the Windows Runtime in JavaScript<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/hh710230.aspx)</ept>.","pos":[6567,6663]},{"content":"The rules for camel casing can be confusing.","pos":[6664,6708]},{"content":"A series of initial uppercase letters normally appears as lowercase, but if three uppercase letters are followed by a lowercase letter, only the first two letters appear in lowercase: for example, a member named IDStringKind appears as idStringKind.","pos":[6709,6958]},{"content":"In Visual Studio, you can build your Windows Runtime component project and then use IntelliSense in your JavaScript project to see the correct casing.","pos":[6959,7109]},{"content":"In similar fashion, the .NET Framework provides support to enable the natural use of the Windows Runtime in managed code.","pos":[7111,7232]},{"content":"This is discussed in subsequent sections of this article, and in the articles <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Creating Windows Runtime Components in C# and Visual Basic<ept id=\"p1\">](creating-windows-runtime-components-in-csharp-and-visual-basic.md)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>.NET Framework Support for Windows Store Apps and Windows Runtime<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/hh694558.aspx)</ept>.","pos":[7233,7561]},{"content":"Create a simple user interface","pos":[7566,7596]},{"content":"In your JavaScript project, open the default.html file and update the body as shown in the following code.","pos":[7599,7705]},{"content":"This code includes the complete set of controls for the example app and specifies the function names for the click events.","pos":[7706,7828]},{"pos":[7832,7920],"content