e JavaScript and the .NET Framework support the Windows Runtime differently.","pos":[12062,12240]},{"content":"The following example demonstrates these differences, using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows.Foundation.Collections.PropertySet<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/windows.foundation.collections.propertyset.aspx)</ept> class.","pos":[12241,12453]},{"content":"In this example, you create an instance of the PropertySet collection in managed code and register an event handler to track changes in the collection.","pos":[12454,12605]},{"content":"Then you add JavaScript code that gets the collection, registers its own event handler, and uses the collection.","pos":[12606,12718]},{"content":"Finally, you add a method that makes changes to the collection from managed code and shows JavaScript handling a managed exception.","pos":[12719,12850]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Important<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  In this example, the event is being fired on the UI thread.","pos":[12854,12928]},{"content":"If you fire the event from a background thread, for example in an async call, you will need to do some extra work in order for JavaScript to handle the event.","pos":[12929,13087]},{"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Raising Events in Windows Runtime Components<ept id=\"p1\">](raising-events-in-windows-runtime-components.md)</ept>.","pos":[13088,13210]},{"content":"In the SampleComponent project, add a new <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>public sealed<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> class (<bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Public NotInheritable<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> class in Visual Basic) named PropertySetStats.","pos":[13215,13354]},{"content":"The class wraps a PropertySet collection and handles its MapChanged event.","pos":[13355,13429]},{"content":"The event handler tracks the number of changes of each kind that occur, and the DisplayStats method produces a report that is formatted in HTML.","pos":[13430,13574]},{"content":"Notice the a